quote: All offenders prepare for dormancy period. Any offender still active during the dormancy period will be disciplined. Illumination will be suspended in twenty seconds.
Quickly.
Sleep well, Miles. And if you feel like laughing in the middle of the night... go ahead. I'm a heavy sleeper.
Dormancy period initiated.
Miles?
Your throw.
Do I need one seventeen, or two?
I'm not sure.
Neither am I.
We could start again.
That's all right. I know darts isn't really your game. And to be honest, I don't feel much like playing either.
We could go kayaking in the holosuite.
You're a good friend, but...
Excuse me.
Is everything all right?
It's fine. I just thought I saw someone I used to know.
Interphasic coil spanner.
ODN recoupler.
You got it.
It's a--
Don't tell me. I'll get it.
A... quantum flux regulator. Mark Three.
Perfect.
Let's go through them again.
Chief, you know this stuff. You don't have to worry about it.
I don't want to embarrass myself in front of the repair crews.
Even if you get one wrong, I'm sure no one'll think anything of it. You may be a little rusty, but you're still the chief.
If I'm still the chief... then I say we go over these again.
Right you are... Chief.
All done here.
That was quick.
I reconfigured the magnetic waveguides. Saved us the trouble of replacing the entire unit.
Good as new. We're about done here. If it's all right with you, I was going to dismiss the crew for lunch.
You go ahead. I want to take a look at a couple of things down here... brush up a little more.
Keep up the good work, crewman. In another week or two you'll be running this place.
And don't you forget it.
Chief... There you are.
Hello, Julian. Here to check up on me?
To be honest... Yes. Counselor Telnorri says you haven't been in to see him in ten days.
So?
So you're supposed to be seeing him three times a week.

What for? All Telnorri ever does is sit there and listen to me tell stories about what it was like to be in an Argrathi prison. How often did they beat me? Was I distressed by the lack of toilet facilities? If you ask me, he's the one with the problem.
You could talk to a different counselor. Someone you might like better.
Julian, I don't want to talk to a counselor. All I want is to forget what happened on Argratha and get on with my life.
Just like that?
That's right. Just like that. I don't need counseling or relaxation or time to adjust. I just want to be left alone.
I would think after being alone for twenty years you'd want someone to talk to.

You know, if there was one thing I didn't miss over the last twenty years, it was your smug, superior attitude. Now I said I wanted to be left alone and I meant it. So if you know what's good for you you'll stay the hell away from me.
Tell me about Keiko again. About how much you like her eyes.
I've told you about her a hundred times. What more is there to say?
I like hearing about her. If I had a beautiful wife to talk about, believe me, I would. Besides talking about her always relaxes you. And your pacing is getting a little distracting.
Well your drawing is bothering me.
Since when?
Since right now.
You didn't need to do that.
Who are you to tell me what I need?
Miles...
Don't "Miles" me. I'm sick of it. I'm sick of your drawings, I'm sick of this place, and most of all I'm sick of you.
Try to be calm.
I don't want to be calm. I've had it with this place. I don't belong here.
Did you hear that? I don't belong here. I didn't do anything wrong.
I know you're listening.
Get me the hell out of here. I don't deserve this and you know it. I didn't do anything wrong. Let me out.
Miles.
All offenders in detention area four, if you do not cease this disturbance immediately, you will be disciplined.
Discipline this you son of a--
Be quiet before you get yourself killed.
Chief. How are you doing?
I wish people would stop asking me that.
I'm sorry, Constable. Everything's fine. I've just... had a tough day.
That was a black hole straight up, right?
A synthale please.
Be right with you, Chief.
Quark. What about that synthale?
Just another minute.
Quark.
Look, Chief, I'm a little busy right-
I'm in no mood for games, Quark. So why don't you give me my drink now or I'll break every bone in your worthless little body.
Chief, just because your life's in shambles is no reason--
I mean it.
One synthale coming right up.
But I'm charging you double.
Miles?
Ee'char? What are you doing here?
I've never really been gone, have I?
You're not real. You're just in my head.
That's all I ever was. But I'm real to you and that's all that matters.
Go away.
I can't. I'm your friend. You need me.
You're the last thing I need.
You're wrong, Miles. You need me. Now more than ever.
What are you doing?
Going to work.
Miles, as your friend, I have to tell you, I'm worried about you.
Don't be. I'm home, I'm working, and for the first time in as long as I can remember, I feel good.
Then why am I here?
Sisko to O'Brien. Please report to my office.
On my way. Look, I don't know why you're here. And I don't care.
Have a seat.
I understand you had a confrontation with Doctor Bashir yesterday.
That? That was nothing.
Not according to Doctor Bashir.
We had a little argument. Julian and I are always arguing.
According to Constable Odo, you also had an incident with Quark.
Did that little-- (catches himself, pulls back) Look, Captain...
I know I let things get a little bit out of hand. But it won't happen again.
Doctor Bashir also tells me that you've stopped seeing your counselor.
I guess I've been a little busy lately, and--
The agreement was, you were to see a counselor on a regular basis.
You're right. I'll make an appointment to go see him tomorrow.
You'll see him today. Immediately.
Sir, I've got a lot of work to do today...
The work can wait.
As of now, you're relieved of duty.
I want you to report to Counselor Telnorri and begin attending daily counseling session for as long as he thinks it's advisable.
You're blowing this all out of proportion.

You know that's not true. You're not yourself, Chief. what happened on Argratha affected you a lot more than you're willing to admit. And it's not going to get better overnight, no matter how much you want it to. You need help.
Captain, please. I'm asking you, as a personal favor to me... give me one more chance.

I wish I could. But right now, in the judgement of this station's chief medical officer, you're unfit for duty. Which means you're on medical leave, effective immediately. And if you don't begin attending counseling sessions on a regular basis, and cooperating in every other way with your physician, I will have no choice but to have you confined to the infirmary. Is that clear?
Yes, sir.
Dismissed.
Chief, I was just about to head down to the Replimat and I was wondering...
Not right now, commander.
Promenade.
What the hell did you say to him?
I take it you talked to Captain Sisko.
I talked to him all right. And he relieved me of duty.
It's for the best, Miles.
How would you know what's best for me? You don't have any idea what I've been going through.
You're right. You were alone in that cell. I wasn't there with you. I didn't see what they did to you. But I do know you suffered. And that you're still suffering right now. And I'm trying to help.
I never asked for your help.
You didn't have to ask. I'm your doctor... and your friend.
You should listen to him, Miles. He cares about you. Just like I did. Don't make the same mistake with him that you did with me.
Don't you get it. You're not my friend. Not anymore. The O'Brien that was your friend died in that cell.
He's not dead. He just needs a little help, that's all.
Stay away from me. I don't want your help, I don't want your friendship. I just want to be left alone.
Where are you going?
I told you to go away.
Miles, please, don't do this. Go back there and talk to him. He wants to help.
Like you did?
That's right. We're both your friends.
Yeah. And look what happened to you.
Habitat Ring.
You know, sooner or later, you'll have to tell someone about me.
Like hell I will.
You can't run from me forever.
scene: 66   INT. ANOTHER PART OF THE CORRIDOR

quote: You're dead. So why don't you just go away and leave me alone.
You want me to leave? I'll leave. Send me away.
Don't you see? If I keep coming back, it's because some part of you keeps bringing me here.
Miles, Julian's been trying to contact you for an hour. Where have you been?
Walking... thinking.
I heard what happened. I'm sorry. I know how much your work means to you.
Try telling that to Julian.
Daddy, come see what I drew.
Not right now, honey.
I'm sure this is only temporary. You'll be back at work before you know it.
Daddy. You have to come see.
Look, can we talk about this later?
Daddy, come on.
Not now.
Please, Daddy, please.
I said not now. Don't you hear what I'm saying? Not now.
Miles.
I didn't mean...
I'm sorry.
Chief?
Get out of here, Julian.
You don't want to do this, Chief.
The hell I don't.
Look, I can't claim to know what you're going through, but whatever it is, it's not worth dying for.
You don't understand at all. I'm not doing this for me. I'm doing this to protect Keiko, and Molly... and everyone else on this station.
Protect us from what?
From me. Don't you get it? I'm not the same man I used to be. I'm dangerous. I almost hit Molly today. Did you know that? All she wanted was a little attention and I almost hit her.
But you didn't. You're a good man, Miles Edward O'Brien. And whatever it is you think you've done wrong, you don't deserve to die.
You sound like Ee'char.
Who's Ee'char?
He wasn't real. He's a memory... that's all.
A memory from Argratha. Who was he? Another prisoner? A guard?
He was my cellmate.
You told me you were alone in that cell. Twenty years with no one to talk to.
Only at the end. A week, maybe two. But the rest of the time... there was Ee'char.
What happened to him?
Why did you stop?
It wasn't helping.
You have to concentrate more.
It doesn't matter how much I concentrate. I'm still starving.
So am I.
You're sure there's nothing left?
Not unless you've got a hiding place I don't know about.
We ate the last of the food I put away a week ago.
We should've stockpiled more. We should've planned for this.
They've never let us go this long without food before.
What if they've forgotten about us... or just decided to finally let us die?
Then we die.
All offenders prepare for dormancy period. Any offender still active during the dormancy period will be disciplined. Illumination will be suspended in twenty seconds.
What are you doing?
I'm going to sleep.
How can you sleep at a time like this?
Maybe I'll dream about food.
You're crazy.
No. Just hungry.
Dormancy period initiated.
I knew it.
You pretended to be my friend and all this time, you've been holding out on me.
Now who's acting crazy?
After all I've done for you. You ungrateful...
You were saving it for both of us.
Ee'char?
Ee'char, wake up. Ee'char!
Ee'char.
You killed him?

(a confession to Ee'char) And the worst part of it was... the next day, the guards started feeding me again. I'd killed him for nothing... for a scrap of bread that he was going to share with me anyway.
It was a mistake. You didn't mean to do it.
No. I meant it. I wanted him to die.

I keep telling myself it doesn't matter. That it wasn't real. But that's a lie. If it'd been real... If it'd been you instead of Ee'char... it wouldn't have made any difference. He was my best friend. And I murdered him. When we were growing up, they used to tell us that humanity had evolved.

That mankind had outgrown hate and rage. But when it came down to it, when I had the chance to prove that no matter what anyone did to me, I was still an evolved human being, I failed. I paid back kindness with blood. I was no better than an animal.

No. An animal would've killed Ee'char and never had a second thought, never shed a tear. But not you. You hate yourself for it. Hate yourself so much you think you deserve to die. And that's what makes you human. The Argrathi did everything they could to strip away your humanity. And in the end, for one brief moment, they succeeded. But you shouldn't let that one moment define your entire life. Because if you do, if you pull that trigger, the Argrathi will have won. They'll have destroyed a good man. And you can't let that happen.
Be well, Miles.
Thirty milligrams twice a day. Take it religiously for a month, and if everything goes well, we'll experiment with a lower dosage.
You sure this'll work?
It's a treatment, not a cure. It'll prevent the hallucinations and take the edge off the depression. But that's all it'll do. It won't take away the memories... or the feelings.
You mean the guilt.
That'll take time.
Now's the part where you tell me I have to start seeing Counselor Telnorri again.
Unless you want to talk to me.
Telnorri will be fine.
Thanks, Julian. For everything.
What are friends for?
Daddy's home, Daddy's home.
That's right, Daddy's home.
Hey, Jake. What's all this?
My science project. I'm growing Bajoran katterpods to find out which hybrid yields the biggest root.
That's it? You're just going to watch them grow?
Yeah. Pretty neat, huh?
Not bad... But don't you think it's a little... (trying to be diplomatic) Low tech.
I'm a low tech kind of guy, dad.
I still think you can do something a little more challenging. If you could do any science project you wanted... anything at all... what would it be?
(knows this is a long shot) Learn how to pilot a runabout?
That's not really a science project, is it? What's your second choice?
Visit the Gamma Quadrant?
What would you do once you got there?
I don't know... I could... do a planetary survey?
That's not bad. All right. Let's do it.
Really?
It'll be like a vacation. A working vacation.
That's fantastic. Thanks, Dad. I bet we'll have a great time.
I know we will.

Let's see, we have a Bolian freighter due in the day after tomorrow... we'll be outfitting another group of settlers leaving for New Bajor... I hear the colony's new irrigation system is something to see. When you get to the Gamma Quadrant, you should take a look.
Not this trip. I really want to spend some time alone with Jake. When's the Odyssey due back from the Cardassian border?
Three days.
It's a shame I'll have to miss your reunion with Captain Keogh.
I'm seven times as old as Keogh, and he treats me like some kind of...
Lieutenant?
Don't you find him just a little arrogant?
Funny, he said the same thing about you.
Did he?
He's the Captain of a Galaxy-class starship and I expect him to be treated with the courtesy he deserves.
Don't worry. I'll be on my best behavior.
You just enjoy your vacation. I'll keep everyone out of trouble until you get back.
I don't doubt it.
Commander... your son's here to see you.
Send him in. He's really looking forward to this trip.
Dad, guess what... I was talking to Nog and it turns out that he's having trouble coming up with a science project. So I told him he could be my partner.
(smiling, to Sisko, re: PADD) I think we can finish this later.
Partner?
We asked Mrs. O'Brien and she said it would be okay, so I invited Nog to come with us to the Gamma Quadrant.
Now hold on a second, Jake...
Dad, if Nog doesn't get a good grade on this science project, he's going to drop out of school. And I can't let that happen.
Maybe he can help you analyze the survey information when we get back.
That's not enough. Mrs. O'Brien said he'd have to be an equal partner. Come on, Dad... he's my friend. I have to help him.
Morn, you've been sitting there all day, staring into the same drink. Talk to me. I want to help. I'm not just your bartender... I'm your friend. Whatever's wrong, I'm here for you.
Hold that thought.
Well... what did he say?
What did who say?
Commander Sisko. About my idea.
You mean using the monitors to sell merchandise throughout the station?
Stop torturing me, Odo. Tell me what he said.
Guess.
He said yes?
Guess again.
But how could he refuse? It would triple my profits.
Maybe it's because he doesn't like you.
Don't be ridiculous. Major Kira is the one that doesn't like me. Sisko...
Doesn't like you either.
What did I ever do to him?
Oh, I could think of one or two things.
One or two things? That's nothing. So do you think there's any way I can change his mind?
Uncle Quark?
Not now.
(trying to soft-sell this) I just wanted to tell you, I'm not going to be able to work my shift for the next couple of days.
Why not?
I'm... going to the Gamma Quadrant... with Jake and his father.
You're going to the Gamma Quadrant with Commander Sisko?
How... Lucky for you.
I always wanted to see what the cockpit of a runabout looked like.
How do you fire the phasers?
Nog, you promised.
I wasn't going to touch anything.
Why don't you guys stow our gear in the back while I go through pre- launch?
I'll do it.
I'll be right there.
Fire the phasers?
He was kidding. Look, Dad. I know this isn't exactly the trip you planned on. But you'll see... Nog's a great guy.
I'm sure he is. I was just hoping that you and I could spend this time... together.
We will. Don't worry. You won't even know Nog's along. This is going to be a great trip. You'll see.
Ah, there you are.
Where do I put my bags?
Uncle Quark... What are you doing here?
What's it look like? I'm coming with you.
Since when?
(doing some fast talking) Really, Commander, you don't expect my nephew to go all the way to the Gamma Quadrant without proper supervision.
No offense... some of my best friends are humans. But my brother Rom isn't as... liberal as I am. Let's face it... he's never been comfortable about Nog's friendship with your son.
You can tell Rom not to worry. I'll take good care of the boy. And I promise I won't try to corrupt him with my human values.
I know that, but Rom is convinced all humans look down on Ferengis. And by allowing me to come on this trip, you can help prove him wrong. He is wrong, isn't he?
Dad, please...
All right. But let's get going before anyone else shows up.
This place is great.
Our preliminary surveys suggest it's a lot like Earth during the early Devonian period. A lot of plant life, fish, some insects, but no predators or large land animals. Pretty, isn't it?
I don't see what's so pretty about it.
I think they mean the trees and stuff.
Look around you, Quark. This is as close to paradise as you'll ever get. You just have to allow yourself to see it.
I can tell you what I see in two words... "exploitable resources."
I suppose you'd want to cut down all these trees and start strip mining the entire planet.
As a wise man once wrote... "Nature decays, but latinum lasts forever."
Rule of Acquisition number one-oh- two?
Good lad. Nog... I have some ointment in one of my bags... get it.
What's the problem?
Oh, I get a mild reaction now and then.
To what?
Nature.
Maybe you'd be more comfortable sleeping on the runabout.
And miss all the fun... never. (giving Sisko a friendly pat on the back) Besides, I'm really looking forward to our getting to know each other better.
Ahh... That's more like it. Now if it only wasn't so hot.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: I hadn't noticed.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: I don't think it's the heat so much as the humidity. And the insects. And the stench of these flowers. I'm glad that we can talk like this. There's nothing like facing the wilderness to bring people closer.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: The answer is still "no," Quark.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: No? No to what?
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: I'm not going to let you sell merchandise over the station's monitors.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: Why not? It's a brilliant idea. There's only room for so many stores on the Promenade. With my connections, I could offer a whole range of merchandise that normally couldn't be acquired in this sector...
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: Such as?
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: Collectibles... Andorian jewelry... Vulcan Idic Pins... Bolian crystalsteel, and with my low overhead, I could offer these items at a significant discount.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: Quark, you're wasting your time. And mine.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: Did I mention I was going to donate two percent of my net profit to the Bajoran Fund for Orphans? Three percent.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: So... how's it going?
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: The atmosphere's seventy-seven percent nitrogen, twenty-one percent oxygen, and two percent carbon dioxide. The water contains traces of copper, nickel and a little birythium...
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: You're showing a little lead there too.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: It's from the surrounding soil. But we think it's localized.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: We're going to check some other water sources to be sure.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: Why not wait until tomorrow? I was just about to start dinner.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: Jumbalaya?
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: How'd you know?
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: Great.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: Jumbowhat?
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: You're gonna love it.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: The two of you did good work today.
scene: 15   EXT. ANOTHER PART OF THE JUNGLE - DAY

quote: Anyone want some more?
Not me.
Me neither... but it was very good, Commander. I think I'm developing a taste for human food.
Quark?
I still say some dirt got into the sauce. And these bugs. Look at this... (he picks a tiny speck out of his food) They get into everything. It's disgusting.
I thought Ferengis liked eating bugs.
Only certain bugs. Ferengi bugs. Nog... get some more ointment for the back of my neck.
Yes, Uncle.
You should get a good night's sleep. You've got another big day tomorrow.
Yeah, I want to start cataloguing the plant life first thing in the morning.
You know what this reminds me of...
That camping trip we took on Itamish Three.
I don't think I remember you, me, and mom ever having more fun together.
Isn't that where I taught you how to water ski?
Mom taught me how to water ski.
She was always the graceful one. You know, Jake... we really need to get away more often.
I'm ready whenever you are. And I'm sure Nog is too. I'm joking.
I'm on fire... I'm on fire...
Are you all right?
No, I'm not all right. My ears itch, my nose is running, I'm eating foreign bugs... and now look at me.
One minute I'm trying to pick out a couple of insects from the jumblewhatsit pot... and next thing I know... whoosh...
Calm down, Quark.
Look, do us all a favor... sit down... and try to stay out of trouble.
What did I do?
(embarrassed for his friend) I'd better see if he's okay.
Now see what you've done.
What I've done?
The boy couldn't stand to see his favorite Uncle insulted. I guess Rom was right after all... You don't like Ferengis, do you?
That's not true.
All right... name me one Ferengi you do like.

Hah. You see? I'm right. You Federation types are all alike. You talk about tolerance and understanding... but you only practice it toward people that remind you of yourselves. Because you disapprove of Ferengi values, you scorn us... distrust us... and insult us every chance you get.
Quark, I don't have to stand here and defend myself...
Tell me, Commander, would you allow your son to marry a Ferengi female?
I never thought about it.
Exactly my point...
Wait... don't be frightened... we --
Don't hurt me.
How many of them are there?
(not sure what she's talking about) There's just the two of us.
Not you. The Jem'Hadar.
We don't know who you're talking about, but we're not your enemies.
Then you'd better run.
It's too late. You're done running.
This has not been a good day.
Dad, this is Jake. Where are you?
I tell you, something's happened to them. Maybe they got attacked by some kind of wild animal.
You heard my father. There aren't any wild animals, just insects and plants.
Maybe they were attacked by a vicious tree.
Take a look at this.
I don't know any trees that wear boots.
We'd better beam up to the runabout.
Listen, we can't run away just 'cause we're scared.
Who said anything about being scared?
I just thought the runabout would be a good place to... plan our next move.
There's nothing to plan. My dad never would've left here without telling me first. Not unless he was in some kind of trouble. We can track them with the tricorder.
Wait for me.
Hey! Is anybody there? Hello! We're humanoids! We require food and water. Hello!
Quark, shut up.
This is your fault... they were after you, not us... why don't you say something to them... ? Tell them you never saw us before.
(continuing, yelling out again) We have nothing to do with her! This is a misunderstanding!
Quark...
I have the right to express my opinion.
I'm about to put my fist in your opinion.
You don't scare me. And you know why you don't scare me? Because I'm already more scared than I've ever been in my life.
You're not helping anything.
I'm not helping. I don't see you coming up with any ideas. Or her.
If she wants to help us, she will. Right now, I'd say she's even more scared than you are.
Believe me, she's not.

She's obviously been running from these people for a while... she's probably been through a lot... she doesn't know who we are, what we're about... when she begins to trust us, maybe she'll work with us to find a way to get out of here...
I just hope Jake and Nog are smart enough to stay out of sight until help gets here...
Trust me. I didn't raise my nephew to be a fool. He'll find the nearest dark hole and climb into it.
I'm not so sure about Jake. If I know him, he'll be looking for us...
Don't they teach you how to neutralize security fields in Starfleet?
I've never seen anything like this... it seems like it's generated by a...
Don't.
The security barrier will kill you.
(reacts to her speaking, smiles) Thanks for the warning.
I have no wish to see you hurt.
A lovely sentiment.
How'd you know the security barrier's lethal?
Because everything about the Jem'Hadar is lethal.
Anything you can tell me about them might be helpful...
Are you saying you've never heard of the Jem'Hadar?
We're not from around here. My name is Ben Sisko, I'm from the United Federation of Planets... we came through a wormhole to get here... our home is thousands of light years away...
My name is Eris.
I'm glad to meet you, Eris. That's Quark.
Tell me about the Jem'Hadar.
They're the most feared soldiers in the Dominion.
The Dominion? The Ferengi have been trying to open up trade negotiations with the Dominion for almost a year now. But we've never met the Jem'Hadar.
Then you've been fortunate. Negotiating with the Dominion can be a dangerous thing.
If it's so dangerous, then why would anyone do business with them?

The Dominion decides you have something they want, and they come and take it... either by negotiation or by force. Believe me, I know. I've seen it happen on my own world. Kurill Prime was offered entry into the Dominion. They thought our telekinetic abilities would be useful to them.
Back there in the camp, that's what you used to knock me down.

When Kurill refused the Dominion's offer, they sent in the Jem'Hadar. They destroyed our communications centers, executed our leaders, and, before we realized it, they had seized control of the entire planet.
How'd you manage to escape?
I was on a freighter returning home when the attack occurred. We fled, but they came after us.
Why?
My mother was an outspoken opponent of the Dominion. I suppose they wanted to make an example of my family.
That thing they put around your neck...
It suppresses my telekinetic abilities. Without it, I might be able to break through the security barrier.
Then we'll just have to find a way to get this collar off.
Even if we do get past the barrier, no one escapes from the Jem'Hadar.
Luckily for us, they seem as sure about that as you do.
Look around you. They've placed the three of us in the same containment field. I've never seen more than four guards on duty at any one time.
And as far as I can tell, there's only this single containment field between us and freedom. They're overconfident. And that's going to help us get out of here.
Maybe if I can pry off that casing, I can get to the locking mechanism.
May I?
Of course.
Are you sure you know how to read that thing?
Pretty sure.
Pretty sure? We've been walking for hours and you're only "pretty sure?"
Would you be quiet? I'm picking up some kind of humanoid lifeforms.
I don't know who they are, but they don't look friendly.
I wish we could get closer.
I don't think they'll look any friendlier close up.
Hello... I know someone must be listening to me out there.
SISKO wheedling) He's not so bad. Whoever's in charge, you're missing a very lucrative ERIS opportunity. Doesn't he realize he's not accomplishing anything?
ERIS opportunity. Doesn't he realize he's not accomplishing anything?

Don't be so sure. We need to find out what the Did I mention I happen to Jem'Hadar plan to do with be a close personal friend us. Which means we need of the Grand Nagus. He's to get their attention. a very powerful person. And If there's one thing Whatever you want for I know... releasing me, he can get. Just name your price.
That's enough.
It's that Quark is hard to ignore.
I'm Commander Benjamin Sisko of the United Federation of Planets. I want to know why we're being held here.
That's not my concern.
Then why won't you let us go?
Because the Founders don't want you released.
And who are the Founders?
That's not your concern.
This isn't getting us anywhere. Commander, allow me.
How would you like a thousand cases of tulaberry wine...
Don't bother, Commander. I'm not going to do any permanent damage.
If the Founders are the ones who give you your orders, I want to meet them.
Those aren't my orders.
He can't take us to the Founders because they don't exist. They're a myth.
The Founders exist. They created the Dominion...
And the Jem'Hadar are their servants?
A Ferengi and a human. I was hoping the first race I'd meet from the other side of the anomaly would be the Klingons.
Sorry to disappoint you.
I'm not interested in discussing the Klingons.
All right. Then what about the Cardassians? Are you satisfied with the treaty your Federation made with them. It seems a tactical error.
How do you know so much about our side of the galaxy?
We gain more knowledge every day. And now we have you to help us learn more.
I don't plan on telling you anything.
I won't be the one asking the questions.
Who will?
I was really hoping to meet a Klingon.
(still rubbing his chest) Well, now that we're all friends, I feel much better.
I hope this works.
You wanted a plan... I came up with a plan. Now let me concentrate. Computer, scan the region around our base camp for human and Ferengi lifesigns.
One human and one Ferengi located.
That's them.
I told you this would work. Computer, lock onto those two lifeforms and beam them up.
Unable to comply. Subjects are located inside a spatial distortion field.
I knew it couldn't be that easy.
Maybe we'd better go back to the station for help.
Good idea. Computer fly us back to the station.
Please restate command.
Computer, disengage autopilot and lay in a course back to the wormhole.
Enter authorization code.
Go ahead. What are you waiting for?
I don't know the authorization code.
Vessel approaching from the planet's surface. Bearing one-seven-three mark two-eight-one.
Computer, evasive maneuvers... Fire Phasers... Launch escape pods.
Enter authorization code.
Computer, display the approaching ship on the monitor.
Computer, where'd that ship go?
The vessel has entered warp, bearing one-seven-one mark two-five-nine.
Maybe they didn't see us.
Or maybe we're not what they're after.
So what do we do now?
We have to shut down the autopilot.
And how do we do that?
I guess we're going to find out how much I've learned working for Chief O'Brien.
Lieutenant, what's the E.T.A. of the Odyssey?
They're due in eight hours... (her attention's drawn to a panel) I'm reading elevated neutrino levels from the wormhole.
Hail them.
They're not answering.
Shields up. Go to yellow alert.
Computer, intruder in Ops. Activate a level three containment field.

I'm Major Kira Nerys, First Officer of this station. You'll have to excuse the containment field, but around here it's customary to identify yourself before transporting into someone else's command center.
I'm Third Talak'Talan of the Jem'Hadar. I'm here to inform you that your commander has been detained for questioning by the Dominion.
Detained? For how long?
Indefinitely.
Commander Sisko will serve as an example of what happens to anyone who interferes with the Dominion.
What kind of interference are you talking about?
Coming through the anomaly is interference enough. Unless you wish to continue to offend the Dominion, I suggest you stay on your side of the galaxy.
You're making a mistake if you think that detaining Commander Sisko will stop us from exploring the Gamma Quadrant.
We anticipated that response.
Security team to Ops.
Here's a list of vessels we've destroyed for violating our territory.
Where'd you get this datapadd.
From the Bajoran colony on our side of the anomaly.
You should be proud. I hear they fought well... for a spiritual people. I hope we won't have to repeat this lesson.
Chief, lock a tractor beam onto his ship.
Acknowledged... I can't establish a lock, Major... (tries to compensate, fails) They must have some kind of deflectors we haven't seen before...
They've entered the wormhole.
Got it.
It looks like some kind of multiple locking system.
Even if I can break through the security barrier, how do you plan on getting off the planet?
We'll try to find my son. We can use his communicator to signal our ship and transport off the surface.
And then what?
You're welcome to come back to the station with us. I'm sure Starfleet would like to hear anything you can tell them about the Dominion.
I'd be glad to tell them all I know.
Quark, maybe you'd better take a look at this.
Sure, "Quark, be quiet." "Quark, stand watch." "Quark, pick a lock." All you ever do is order me around. You know, Commander, I think I've figured out why humans don't like Ferengis.
Not now, Quark.
The way I see it, humans used to be a lot like Ferengis. Greedy, acquisitive, interested only in profit. We're a constant reminder of a part of your past you'd rather forget.
Quark, we don't have time for this.

But you're overlooking something. Humans used to be a lot worse than the Ferengi. The Hundred Years War, Auschwitz, the Tarsus Four Massacre... we have nothing in our past that even approaches that kind of barbarism. (driving home his point) You see, we're nothing like you. We're better.
Now if you'll excuse me, I have a lock to pick.
This shouldn't be so hard. I just watched Chief O'Brien run a maintenance check on the Mekong's navigational array a couple of weeks ago...
(staring at the scattered components) From the looks of things, you weren't watching close enough.
Try that one.
I don't think that's it.
Try it. I've got a hunch.
All right. Let's see.
Warning... Warp core collapse in ten seconds... nine... eight...
Put it back! Put it back!
Seven... six...
Warp core containment field stabilized.
Sorry.
Wait a second... The "G and N" relay.
What about it?

I think O'Brien said something about the autopilot being connected to the guidance and navigation relay... If I could just find it... It was kind of round, except it had this square part, on the bottom... or was it the top.
Don't ask me.
There... I think I got it. Okay... If that's the relay, then...
Is that it?
I hope so. Computer, what's the status of the autopilot?
The automatic pilot system is not functional.
Lay in a course for the wormhole... at warp eight.
Unable to comply. The automatic pilot system is not functional.
Now what?
I guess we'll have to try and fly it ourselves.
Starfleet's orders are simple. Traffic through the wormhole will be suspended until the Odyssey can investigate the Jem'Hadar's threat.
What about Benjamin and the others?
Don't worry, Lieutenant. Commander Sisko's return is a top priority.
If you're going to try to rescue them, we're coming with you.
Are you sure that's wise? With the exception of Major Kira and Mister O'Brien, none of you have had much
We fought the Maquis.
All the Maquis had were a pair of lightly armed shuttlecraft. I expect the Dominion to have sharper teeth.
Then you're going to need all the help you can get.
Mister O'Brien, can you equip your two remaining Runabouts with extra banks of photon torpedos?
I've already started retrofitting their weapons systems. They'll be ready in a few hours.
It'll take at least that long to offload all the nonessential personnel from the Odyssey. You were planning on doing that, weren't you?
Lieutenant, have you ever thought of serving on a starship?
I'm happy where I am.
Good. Major, be ready to leave at thirteen hundred hours.
Yes, sir.
I'll be aboard the Odyssey if you need me.
I thought you said Keogh didn't like you.
Did I say that?
Come on. You heard him. We've got three hours.

Station security is to be on maximum alert... I want random patrols of all corridors and periodic sensor sweeps of every level. The Provisional Government has agreed to send us a detachment of extra security personnel. (he gives the deputy a PADD) This outlines how I want them deployed.
Odo...
Major. That'll be all.
Captain Keogh wants us to move up our departure time. We've got to be ready in fifteen minutes.
I'm on my way to meet Chief O'Brien and Lieutenant Dax at the Mekong right now.
Are you sure you don't want to stay and oversee things here on the station? I don't know what we're going to be up against once we get there. Your duties don't require you to come with us.
I realize that. But I figure while you and the others are trying to rescue Sisko and the boys, someone better be there to look out for Quark.
Quark? I thought you hated Quark.
I do. But I'd rather see him in jail than in the hands of the Dominion. (a beat, a slight admission) Believe me, Major, if anything happened to him, you'd miss him too.
I'd be willing to take that chance. But not today.
I'd better get to the Orinoco. Odo... keep your head down.
Make sure you do the same.
Where's the welcoming committee?
Maybe the Jem'Hadar were bluffing.
Or maybe it's a trap.
Odyssey to runabouts.
Go ahead, Captain.
(on monitor, in background) Preliminary tachyon scans are negative.
We're not detecting anything on long range scanners, but for all we know, the Dominion could have cloaking technology.
We'll keep our eyes open, sir.
I'm telling you, we should go to warp.
First let me get the hang of flying at impulse.
How hard can it be?
Are you kidding? You think making course corrections manually is easy?
But at this speed, it'll take weeks to get home.
Actually, it'll take about five years.
Can't we reassemble the autopilot?
If Chief O'Brien taught me anything, it's that it's a lot easier to take things apart than put them back together.
Warning. Three ships coming out of warp.
Where?
Right there.
Mekong to Rio Grande.
Chief... It's me, Jake.
Jake, are we glad to find you. Where's your father?
He and Quark were taken prisoner.
Jake, come to a full stop. I'll beam aboard.
Have some trouble getting her out of orbit?
How'd you know?
Chief, we've got to go back and save my dad.
Don't worry, son. That's exactly what we're going to do.
This is a very sophisticated device. Most telepathic suppressors I've seen have been much bulkier. You know, there could be a market for this in the Alpha Quadrant.
You're hurting me.
I'm sorry. But I don't have much to work with.
You've been at it for hours.
If you'd just stay still, I'd be...
...done.
All right, let's get out of here.
Stand back.
Quark, move it.
Right behind you.
Thanks.
You're welcome.
I'm picking up something on forward scanners.
Odyssey to runabouts.
Go ahead, Odyssey.
We're detecting three incoming ships in attack formation.
Shields up.
Going to red alert.
Take the helm, Odo. I'll handle the targeting controls.
Very good.
Captain, this is the Rio Grande. Half the systems on this ship are disabled. I'm going to have to break formation.
Understood. Return to the wormhole. We'll try to screen you from enemy fire.
What about my dad?
Captain, I'd like to see if I can get close enough to the planet to locate Commander Sisko.
All right, but you have ten minutes, then I want you out of there.
Enemy ships within range.
Ready to fire at your command.
Runabouts break formation. Attack pattern Delta.
Here they come.
I'm getting casualty reports from decks four, five, eight and seventeen and we have a plasma leak in our port nacelle.
Deploy damage control teams. Keogh to runabouts.
Go ahead.
They're using some kind of phased polaron beam to penetrate our shields.
Have you tried altering your harmonics to compensate?
We rotated through the full spectrum , but none of the frequencies were effective. Divert your shield power to weapons. We'll give O'Brien five more minutes, and then we're getting out of here.

We're with you.
Hang on.
Wait... stop...
(re: his terrible physical condition) I've got to start using those holosuite exercise programs.

I'm not leaving him behind. We never would've gotten away from the Jem'Hadar without him.
Thank you, Commander. I'm glad someone around here appreciates me.
Dad.
This has turned into some science project, huh, Jake?
Uncle Quark...
Nog, you are never going on a "field trip" again.
Take Eris and Nog back to the passenger compartment... And stay there.
And Jake... You did good.
My control panel is dead...
We've lost our sensors.
Break off, Mekong. Initiate evasive maneuvers. We'll lay down covering fire.
Acknowledged.
Rio Grande to Odyssey. We've got Sisko.
Well done, Chief.
(shouting orders in background) Damage control team to level seven. Our tactical control systems are down. We've lost power to phasers.
Bridge to Engineering, get that port nacelle back on line.
Aye, Captain.
Keogh to runabouts, we've got what we came for. We'd better fall back to...
Their communications array must've been hit.
Kira, Dax, you heard him. Let's get out of here.
Major... one of the Jem'Hadar ships is making a direct run at the Odyssey.
Move to intercept.

They're showing us how far they're willing to go. Set a course for the wormhole.
Commander, wait.
We need to talk.
I can't believe I'm on the other side of the galaxy.
You'll get used to it.
Move away from her.
I don't understand.

(holding up the suppression collar) I've been looking over this collar of yours. I thought if I could replicate it, I might be able to turn a tidy profit. Imagine my surprise when I discovered there's nothing in here. It's just a complicated locking device.
Which means you could've used your telekinetic abilities at any time. So the question is, why didn't you?
You seem to already know the answer.
The Jem'Hadar wanted us to escape, didn't they? That was the plan all along... for us to bring you back here, so that you could spy on the Federation.
Well done, Commander.
You're one of the Founders, aren't you?
You think the Founders would waste their time with you?
Constable...
Madam, if you'll come with us...
You have no idea what's begun here.
I'm picking up a transporter signature, but I can't trace it. She didn't rematerialize anywhere on the station and there are no ships nearby.
Then where is she?
She'll be back. The question is... who she'll bring with her?
If the Dominion comes through the wormhole, the first battle will be fought here. And I intend to be ready for them.
Dabo!
You're not leaving?
Well...
Come on... aren't you feeling... lucky?
All right... one more time. Let it ride.
I love this game.
"I love this game."
Oh... Karjinko. Sorry.
Wait a minute there... my name's Okalar... what's yours?
"Busy."
You... are evil.
Who, me?
He was going to walk away a winner...
The first rule of dabo is watch the wheel, not the girl.
"... the wheel, not the girl."

Not to mention the fact that Quark was watching me every second... if I didn't at least try to keep that money in the house, he would've fired me on the spot. And, you're a fine one to talk after hustling that poor Berellian at dom- jot yesterday.
It was a fair game.
Uh huh.
It was.
I believe you.
So what's on the menu tomorrow night? Tomorrow night? Dinner? With your father?
What?
He didn't tell you? He came by this afternoon and invited me to dinner tomorrow night. In fact, he said it was your idea.
My idea... ? Oh... I guess I did mention something
This is all right, isn't it? I mean... you don't mind, do you?
Oh, no... no, of course not...
It'll be great. You're going to love my dad's cooking.
This is a surprise.
A pleasant one, I hope.
So do I...
I have some... salvage for you, Quark.
This isn't the best day to be selling your kind of... "salvage."
Oh, it's perfectly legal... and it's really salvage this time.
I'm not looking for junk right now... I'm more in the market for... entertainment.
I think you'll like this junk, Quark. It's the wreckage of a ship that crashed in the Gamma Quadrant.
You're still going to the Gamma Quadrant? I love bold women. How much?
Three bars of latinum and you get it all.
What kind of ship?
I don't know.
Can I see it first?
No time. Come on, Quark... we've been doing business for years... don't you trust me?
Three bars of latinum...
It was worth it.
No...
No, no, no...
You bought a child.
I thought I was just buying some wreckage... how was I supposed to know there was a baby in there?
Maybe you should inspect the merchandise before making the deal... or isn't there a rule of acquisition covering that?
There is, and I do... usually.
We haven't been able to trace the Boslic Captain since she left the station. Her flight plan said she's headed for Risa, but I don't think we can put much faith in that.
I haven't been able to identify his species yet, but he seems to be healthy...
Seems?

For a humanoid, he has an incredibly high metabolic rate. The cells in his body are dividing at a pace I've never seen outside of a laboratory. Since there're no thyroid or hypothalamic problems, I can only assume this is normal for his species... but I think he should remain here for further tests.
Very well. What do we know about the ship the boy was on?
Chief O'Brien's just started analyzing the wreckage. He should have a preliminary report in a couple of hours.
Now wait a minute -- I paid good money for that wreckage and...
... now it's yours. Enjoy.
Hi there...
We should contact one of the orphanages on Bajor and let them know we might have someone for them.
Hmmm?
I was talking about an orphanage...
Oh. Right. Have Major Kira make the appropriate arrangements. And keep me informed about... him.
Yes, sir.
What?
I haven't seen that look on your face since...
... since Jake stopped wearing diapers.
I never thought I'd hear myself saying this... but I miss taking care of Jake when he was a baby. I miss holding him... singing to him at night... feeding him...
Listening to him cry... changing his diapers... worrying when he was sick...
I haven't forgotten... But there are times when I would give almost anything for the days when I could make Jake happy... just by lifting him over my head.
Jake... how about a hug for your old man?
Why didn't you tell me you were going to invite Mardah to dinner?
I did. Weeks ago. I told you if you didn't invite her soon, I'd do it myself.
I still wish you'd given me a little more warning.
I didn't realize a dinner invitation required so much... warning.
It doesn't... and it's not a problem or anything. It just... caught me by surprise.
Dinner's not until tomorrow night... which still gives you a full day to prepare her for the traumatic experience of eating with your old man.
Yeah. I mean, there's nothing to prepare her for... it's just dinner.
Exactly.
Right.
Right...
You wanted to see me, Doctor?
It's about our new visitor...
Something wrong with the baby?
No... but it's not a baby anymore.

There are a great many species with what we would consider accelerated growth rates. But they're usually small, physiologically simple creatures. I've never heard of such a rapid maturation process in anything as complex as a humanoid.
He looks about... eight or nine... how old is he in really?
From his cellular kinetics profile, I'd say he's no more than two weeks of age.
Who are you?
I'm Benjamin Sisko, this is Doctor Bashir. Do you have a name?
No. I need food.
With your kind of metabolism, I'm not surprised. I'll get you something in a few minutes.
Where am I?
You're on a space station. Do you know what that is?
No. But I want to learn.
I'd say we have a lot to learn from each other.
I'll be right back.
Advanced language skills...

And cognitive reasoning. He didn't just pick those up by sitting there listening to us... this is either a natural ability of his species or there's been some kind of basic intelligence implanted into his genetic structure.
Implanted? You mean artificially?
Yes. And I tend to discount the possibility that this is a natural ability... his biomolecular diffusion gradient already suggests that his cellular mitosis has been artificially enhanced.
So he may have been part of some kind of experiment.
Possibly. If so, he's an example of very advanced genetic engineering... his cognitive abilities are developing without any external stimuli.
I want you to test his mental abilities... see if they increase... maybe he'll get to the point where he can tell us who he is and where he comes from.
This is where Quark said he found the boy. It seems to be some kind of stasis chamber that was damaged in the crash.
That could imply that they didn't want him to begin maturing while he was aboard. What about the rest of the wreckage?
It seems to indicate this was some kind of freighter or transport vessel.
Have you found any computer equipment or other information systems?
Not yet. Most of it is just junk... twisted bulkheads... burnt deck plating... that sort of thing. We should have a complete inventory done by tomorrow morning.
Good.
Oh... by the way... the replicator in my quarters is on the blink again. Could you spare someone to fix it this afternoon?
That shouldn't be a problem. That's right... tonight's the big dinner with Mardah.
You know about that?
Jake mentioned it this morning. In fact, I'd say it was the only thing on his mind.
You'd think I was going to court martial her by the way he's acting.
I guess it's only natural. Bringing a girl home for the first time's a pretty traumatic experience.
Quark may call her a dabo girl... but she's twenty years old. She's a woman... and Jake's a sixteen-year- old boy. It has to stop.
So why'd you invite her over? If you don't mind my asking.
Curiosity, mostly. I want to see what I'm up against.
But what if it turns out that you... like her?
She's a dabo girl and she's dating my son. I don't want to like her.
Sixteen years old and dating a dabo girl... ... Godspeed, Jake.
Major.
Odo.
For you. odo Ah. Let me guess... decoration for my new quarters.
Just a little something to brighten the room up.
That was very... thoughtful.
You're welcome.
I... suppose you'd like to see my quarters.
Everyone wants to see your quarters. It's called curiosity.
It's not really finished yet. This is just the start.
The start of what?
I want to make this room into a place where I can explore what it truly means to be a Shape-shifter.
I thought it was something like that. After all, you don't need an entire set of quarters just to sit in your bucket.
I don't use the... bucket anymore. I've kept it as a reminder of how I used to be. But now, when I need to regenerate, I simply revert to my gelatinous state... anywhere in these rooms.
Here, I can experiment with different shapes and textures... bring in various forms to emulate... and I can do it in private.
I'm sorry if I intruded... maybe I should go.
No, please. You're always welcome here, Major.
Well... where should I put it?
Perfect.
The boy's DNA sequence has definitely been altered... the nucleotide analysis proved that conclusively.
So he's a product of genetic engineering... but why? Was he a unique experiment or is this sort of thing common to his species?
There's more... his blood chemistry shows he's missing a key isogenic enzyme... and without large quantities of it his entire circulatory system will simply shut down.
Can you replicate the enzyme?
I've been trying and I think I've found a temporary substitute... but what I can't understand is why anyone would genetically engineer someone to have a such an obvious flaw.
Nurse Hortak to Doctor Bashir. You're needed in the Infirmary immediately, Doctor.
On my way.
It's all right... no one's going to hurt you... let's just go back inside and--
Security to the Promenade.
Stop! Stay where you are!
Dax to Sisko.
Go ahead.
I think we've solved the mystery of our young visitor, Benjamin... he's a Jem'Hadar.
I've just spoken with Starfleet Command. They want us to make sure he's healthy enough to travel and then send him to Starbase Two-Oh-One where he'll be handed over to a team of specialists.
Sounds good to me... the sooner, the better.
What sort of... specialists are we talking about, Commander?
They'll have a complete team of experts in xenobiology, and exo- psychology waiting for him.
So... they're going to "study" him... like a laboratory specimen.
He'll be very well treated.
So he'll be a well treated specimen.
I agree with Odo, Commander. I don't think we should just ship this boy off like some biological sample that we've found. He's a sentient life form.
True, but the Founders may have removed his sense of free will. He may be nothing more than... a genetically programmed killing machine.

It's my understanding that's one of the first questions the experts at Starfleet want to answer. After all, the threat of the Dominion isn't going to just disappear. We need to learn all we can about the Jem'Hadar.
I agree. And we don't want one of them walking around this station.
Fine. If you want answers about the Jem'Hadar I'm the one who can get them for you. Let me get to know him. I'll be responsible for his conduct while he's here.
Odo... do you really think you can control him?
He's already shown a certain... deference to me. That's probably another genetic alteration implanted by the Founders to insure the Jem'Hadar would remain loyal. I can keep him from harming anyone.
I'd like to speak with the Constable in private for a moment, please.
Talk to me, Odo. What's really going on here?
What the Founders did to this boy... to all the Jem'Hadar... that's not your fault...

Maybe not. But I do feel a certain... obligation to undo some of the damage that my race has done to this boy. But I also know what it's like to be a specimen in a laboratory. Oh, I'm sure they'll treat him well... no one will risk damaging their new prize. They'll be friendly... caring... treat him like he's among friends. But in the end, he'll just be another specimen to them... something to be analyzed and cataloged... and then stored away in a cabinet when they're done.
Give me a chance to find out if he's really just a "programmed killing machine"... or if we can help him become something else.
I'll tell Starfleet that we have... some preliminary tests to run before we send him to Starbase Two-Oh-One.
Thank you, Commander.
Just... be careful, Odo. Don't let your... feelings blind you to the fact that he is still a Jem'Hadar.
Listen to me... I'm trying to help. Your body is craving a certain chemical compound... that's why you're feeling anxious and having muscle spasms.
There's nothing wrong with me.
Yes, there is... and denying it won't make it go away.
Leave me alone.
Sit down, please.
You can wait outside... I think everything is under control now.
You don't look well. How do you feel?
There's... something wrong with me. I feel sick when I eat... I have pains in my head... my chest...
His body is... addicted to a specific isogenic enzyme... right now, he's experiencing all the symptoms of withdrawal.
Addicted...
That's right.
Can you replicate this enzyme?
I've had some success with triglycerides, but that's just a stopgap measure. I can't get the exact chemical formula without further tests... and he's shown a certain... resistance to that idea.
I don't want any more tests.
Doctor Bashir is trying to help you. You should let him.
You may run your tests.
Thank you.
My name is Odo.
I don't have a name.
We'll have to do something about that.
If you wish.
What do you want? Do you have any needs or desires of your own?
I want to fight.
Who? Me?
No. The others.
Why?
I... don't know. It's... what I want to do. Is that wrong?
Let's just say we should find other interests for you to pursue. For the moment, why don't you relax. Try not to be so tense... take it easy... smile.
A smile... you know...
We'll work on that.
Hmmm... smells good. What is it?
Creole shrimp with Mandalay sauce... one of my father's recipes.
You're going to love this...
I hope you like spicy food... because this has a bite to it...
So... Mardah... tell me a little about yourself.
What do you want to know?
Anything... your family.

There's not much to tell... it's a pretty familiar story... parents killed during the occupation... raised by neighbors until I was thirteen, then I moved out on my own. I have a brother and a sister on Bajor... but we haven't talked in years.
Why not?
We're... different. Sarjeno and Koran weren't exactly thrilled when I told them I had a job as a dabo girl... I told them what I thought of their lives... and we stopped speaking.
I see.
It's amazing how some people will judge you based on nothing more than your job...
This is really good, Commander.
Glad you like it. Not too spicy?
Not at all. I like things with a bite.
Did I mention that Mardah's... quite a writer?
Really?
Yeah... Mrs. O'Brien used to say that Mardah should try to get some of her stories published.
Jake... they aren't that good. Nothing like your poetry.
You don't have enough faith in yourself...
Poetry? You write poetry?
Sort of... not really...
Now who doesn't have enough faith in themselves... ? He writes some of the most beautiful things I've ever read... (she takes Jake's hand) That's what won me over.
His... poetry.
And the way he plays dom-jot.
You play dom-jot?
Oh, your son is quite the hustler.
A hustler...
I've never cheated anybody...
I'm sure you haven't.
Why don't I see how dessert's coming?
He seemed like just another teenaged boy at first... but there's more to him than that... he's full of surprises...
I'm beginning to realize that myself.
And... I care about him very much.
So do I. (beat, then with a smile) Now tell me more about my hustler- poet son.
I think it's over here... right, this is it.
We tried to run an analysis, but the computer couldn't make heads or tails of it. Do you really think this is the drug the boy's addicted to?
It seems logical that the Founders would've kept a supply of the enzyme aboard his ship. Hopefully Doctor Bashir can determine if this is it.
I still don't understand why they would engineer someone to be addicted to a certain chemical.

I suspect it's another way of insuring the loyalty of the Jem'Hadar to the Founders. If your soldiers are addicted to a drug that can't be replicated and only you can provide, that gives you a great deal of control over them.
That's a pretty... cold-blooded thing to do.
My people... don't even have blood, Chief.
I believe this tube delivers the chemical agent directly into the carotid artery.
How large of a dosage is required?
I'm not sure yet.
This could be a week's supply... or a month's... or a year's. I'll have to experiment to find the right dosage.
All right... we're going to start with two milligrams per minute, in a one cc saline solution. Let me know if you feel any discomfort.
His heart rate is slowing... some increase in neurotransmitter activity... cortical impulse readings have leveled out. Let's try three cc's.
I think we'll hold it there for now. How do you feel?
Good. Thank you.
You should rest now. We'll talk later. I'll be in my quarters.
Wait. I... want to go with you.
The doctor will take care of you.
I want to stay with you.
He doesn't have to stay here as long as I can monitor his condition regularly.
Then... it would seem I have my first... houseguest.
So you can change into any of these objects... ?
With varying degrees of success. Some forms are more difficult to emulate than others.
Like what?
Like this one. As you can see, I haven't mastered the humanoid face. I've found it to be quite... challenging.
Why do you want to look like a humanoid? You're better than they are. You're... a changeling.
That doesn't make me better... just different.
But I know... ... in here that I'm inferior to you... and that everyone else here is inferior to me.
No... that may be what your instincts tell you. But it's not true. No one on this station is better than anyone else. We're all... equal.
Then I must be at fault... because I know that you can't be wrong.
